---
import GazetteMasthead from '../components/GazetteMasthead.astro';
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import '../styles/guide.css';

const description =
  'A maker’s note on how this edition is set: the Fell and Caslon types, the newspaper columns, Knuth–Plass justification, and the quiet wear on every sheet.';

const pageURL = Astro.site ? new URL('/colophon/', Astro.site).href : undefined;
const jsonLd = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'WebPage',
  name: 'Colophon — How This Edition Is Made',
  description,
  ...(pageURL ? { url: pageURL, mainEntityOfPage: pageURL } : {})
};
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Colophon — How This Edition Is Made | Federalist Reader"
  description={description}
  pageClass="colophon-page"
  ogType="article"
  jsonLd={jsonLd}
>
  <article class="paper-sheet colophon-page">
    <GazetteMasthead compact dateLine="A note on the making" />

    <header class="guide-lead">
      <p class="section-kicker">Colophon</p>
      <h1>How this edition is made</h1>
      <p class="guide-lead__standfirst">
        A maker’s note on the types, the columns, and the wear—the staging that serves the
        reading.
      </p>
      <span class="guide-lead__ornament" aria-hidden="true"></span>
    </header>

    <section class="colophon-section" aria-labelledby="voices-heading">
      <h2 id="voices-heading">The two voices</h2>
      <p>
        Two families of type share this site, and the line between them is the closest thing the
        edition has to a law. IM Fell English sets the Gazette’s paper titles and recipient lines;
        IM Fell DW Pica carries the essay text. Everything modern—the companion notes, the
        guides, Reader mode—speaks in Libre Caslon Display and Libre Caslon Text. Fell speaks
        only when the historical document does.
      </p>
      <p>
        An honest admission belongs here: a 1787 New York paper would most likely have been set in
        Caslon. The Fell types are seventeenth-century Oxford—a century earlier and an ocean away
        from Publius. But their worn, irregular letterforms carry the feel of hand-set metal better
        than anything cleaner I tried, and I chose the feeling over the footnote.
      </p>
      <p>
        The costume stops where reading suffers. There is no long s in this edition—no{' '}
        <i lang="en" translate="no">Congreſs</i> to decipher—because readability outranks period
        dress. What stayed: the ligatures the Fell fonts genuinely carry, and the œ in the heading
        every essay runs under,{' '}
        <span class="colophon-fell" aria-hidden="true">The Fœderalist.</span>
        <span class="visually-hidden">The Federalist.</span>{' '}
        Reader mode sets both aside for modern spellings, and screen readers always hear the modern
        words.
      </p>
    </section>

    <div class="guide-rule" aria-hidden="true"><span class="guide-rule__mark"></span></div>

    <section class="colophon-section" aria-labelledby="newspaper-heading">
      <h2 id="newspaper-heading">Set like a newspaper</h2>
      <p>
        The sheet is composed the way its models were. A masthead lockup crowns each page, its
        dateline set between fine double rules. The text runs in real newspaper columns—one on a
        phone, up to three on a wide screen, never more than each column can carry legibly—divided
        by hairline rules.
      </p>
      <p>
        Each essay opens with a single drop cap, the only one it gets. There is no byline above the
        text, because the originals carried none; at the foot of the final column, Publius signs
        flush right, letterspaced, as in the first printings.
      </p>
    </section>

    <div class="guide-rule" aria-hidden="true"><span class="guide-rule__mark"></span></div>

    <section class="colophon-section" aria-labelledby="justified-heading">
      <h2 id="justified-heading">Justified, at last</h2>
      <p>
        Until July of 2026 these sheets were set ragged right—an edge no 1787 compositor would
        have tolerated. Hand-set newsprint was justified; the Gazette wasn’t, and it bothered me.
      </p>
      <p>
        The columns are justified now, with Knuth–Plass line breaking—the algorithm Donald Knuth
        and Michael Plass published in 1981, and the one TeX has used ever since. It came by way
        of <a href="https://github.com/lyallcooper/justif">justif</a>, Lyall Cooper’s library,
        which surfaced in{' '}
        <a href="https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48946738">a Show HN thread</a> in mid-July;
        within the week it was running here. Where a browser justifies one line at a
        time and stretches whatever comes up short, justif considers the whole paragraph at once,
        so the spacing stays even and the rivers drain away.
      </p>
      <p>
        The before-and-after, at the Gazette’s exact column measure, is in the{' '}
        <a href="/notes/justif/">field notes</a>. Reader mode stays ragged left on purpose: for
        modern reading, even word spacing is kinder than a flush margin.
      </p>
    </section>

    <div class="guide-rule" aria-hidden="true"><span class="guide-rule__mark"></span></div>

    <section class="colophon-section" aria-labelledby="size-heading">
      <h2 id="size-heading">Reading at your size</h2>
      <p>
        Beside the Gazette-or-Reader toggle sits a five-step text-size control. It drives a single
        value, <code>--reading-scale</code>, which multiplies the essay and companion prose. The
        column measures scale with it, so enlarged text reflows into fewer, wider columns rather
        than cramped narrow ones. Mastheads, headings, and rules never scale: the furniture holds
        still while the reading grows. The choice is remembered in your browser and applied before
        the page first paints.
      </p>
    </section>

    <div class="guide-rule" aria-hidden="true"><span class="guide-rule__mark"></span></div>

    <section class="colophon-section" aria-labelledby="wear-heading">
      <h2 id="wear-heading">The wear</h2>
      <p>
        Every sheet is worn, and no two are worn alike. When the site is built, each paper’s
        number seeds a stable material fingerprint: deckled edges with small nicks, softened
        corners, a single lifted corner on roughly two sheets in three, and a warm tea-tan browning
        at the perimeter that ages the corners hardest. Each paper always looks like
        itself—revisit No. 10 in a year and its dog-ear will not have moved.
      </p>
      <p>
        The restraint matters more than the distress. No stains, no burns, no damage theater: the
        sheets read as carefully preserved, not neglected. Wear never touches the text, and it
        withdraws entirely in Reader mode, in print, and for readers who ask for high contrast or
        reduced transparency.
      </p>
    </section>

    <div class="guide-rule" aria-hidden="true"><span class="guide-rule__mark"></span></div>

    <section class="colophon-section" aria-labelledby="for-heading">
      <h2 id="for-heading">What it’s all for</h2>
      <p>
        All of this staging serves the reading, never the other way around. The words are the
        authors’ own, following the{' '}
        <a href="https://www.gutenberg.org/files/1404/1404-h/1404-h.htm">Project Gutenberg text</a>
        {' '}that the{' '}
        <a href="https://guides.loc.gov/federalist-papers/full-text">Library of Congress’s full-text guide</a>
        {' '}itself relies on. The notes stay short, and the whole edition is free—no accounts, no
        advertising. The story behind the project is on the <a href="/about/">About page</a>.
      </p>
      <p class="guide-cta">
        <a class="button-link" href="/papers/1/">Begin with Paper No. 1 <span aria-hidden="true">→</span></a>
      </p>
    </section>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .colophon-section {
    max-inline-size: 56ch;
    margin: var(--space-xl) auto 0;
  }

  .colophon-section h2 {
    text-align: center;
    font: 400 clamp(1.5rem, 3vw, 2.1rem) / 1.1 var(--font-display);
  }

  .colophon-section p {
    margin-block-start: var(--space-md);
    font-size: 1.0625rem;
    line-height: 1.65;
    text-wrap: pretty;
  }

  .colophon-fell {
    font-family: var(--font-period-display);
    font-variant-ligatures: common-ligatures historical-ligatures;
  }

  .colophon-section code {
    font-family: ui-monospace, 'SF Mono', Menlo, monospace;
    font-size: 0.88em;
  }
</style>
